<subSubSection pageId="66" pageNumber="67" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="66.[151,1436,152,1338]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,326,1195,1221]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Remarks.</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Lea, A. M." box="[337,478,1196,1222]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" pagination="471 - 512" refId="ref49316" refString="Lea, A. M. (1922) On Australian Anthicidae (Coleoptera). Proceedings of the Linnean Society of New South Wales, 47, 471 - 512." type="journal article" year="1922">Lea (1922)</bibRefCitation>
described the elytra of 
<taxonomicName box="[790,999,1196,1221]" class="Insecta" family="Anthicidae" genus="Formicomus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pubifasciatus">
<emphasis box="[790,999,1196,1221]" italics="true" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">C. pubifasciatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as unicolourous and having “two interrupted fasciae of white pubescence: one at the basal third, the other at the apical third”. In the 
<typeStatus box="[1332,1435,1234,1260]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">holotype</typeStatus>
examined, these setose bands are now almost completely abraded and indistinct, except for small patches of moderately swirled whitish setae in the apical third.
</paragraph>
